Probably=C2=A0Donald Trump should have just issued a crypto token, called i=
t =E2=80=9CDJT,=E2=80=9D gone around saying =E2=80=9Cthis is the crypto tok=
en of me, Donald Trump,=E2=80=9D kept 90% of it for himself, and let it tra=
de. People who like Trump would buy it, it would go up, his stake would be =
worth billions of dollars, and he could sell tokens to raise money for hims=
elf. Just a straightforward memecoin. I suppose the problem with this is th=
at Trump has a lot of older, less crypto-native fans, and this would not be=
 an effective way to tap them for money.
But you can get arbitrarily close to this =E2=80=94=C2=A0while attracting a=
 more traditional investor base =E2=80=94=C2=A0by issuing a=C2=A0stock=C2=
=A0called DJT, and Trump did. DJT =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ticker symbol of Trump=
 Media & Technology Group Corp. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a meme stock with a marke=
t capitalization, as of yesterday=E2=80=99s close, of about $7 billion. It =
is the stock token of him, Donald Trump, and he owns about 58% of it. Peopl=
e who like Trump bought it, it went up, his stake is worth billions of doll=
ars, and he will eventually be able to sell shares to raise money for himse=
lf, though there is a six-month lockup.=C2=A0
It is a small technical problem that you probably cannot=C2=A0just=C2=A0do =
this. You cannot=C2=A0just=C2=A0issue stock that is like =E2=80=9Cthis is t=
he stock with my name on it, go buy it!=E2=80=9D You can=E2=80=99t start a =
company and take it public to be purely a meme stock.=C2=A0I cannot give yo=
u a really crisp=C2=A0explanation of why not. I am not aware of any provisi=
on of US securities law that is like =E2=80=9Cif you raise money for a publ=
ic company, it has to do something, or at least try.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s =
just, you know. If you say =E2=80=9CI am launching a company with my name o=
n it, and that=E2=80=99s it,=E2=80=9D then underwriters probably will not w=
ant to work with you, and lawyers will be confused writing the prospectus, =
and eventually the US Securities and Exchange Commission will have to sign =
off on the prospectus and will find reasons not to.=C2=A0
But, again, you can get arbitrarily close. You can take a teeny tiny operat=
ing business,=C2=A0wrap=C2=A0it in a meme stock, and sell that. The most fa=
mous example =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s not exactly a meme stock, but clos=
e enough =E2=80=94=C2=A0was the New Jersey deli that=C2=A0had $13,976 of re=
venue and a=C2=A0$2 billion market capitalization. Or, I mean: There was a =
deli, it had $13,976 of revenue, it was the only operating business of a pu=
blic company, and that public company had a $2 billion market capitalizatio=
n. But it wasn=E2=80=99t like =E2=80=9Cpeople were paying $2 billion for th=
at deli.=E2=80=9D The=C2=A0stock=C2=A0traded at $2 billion,=C2=A0for other=
=C2=A0reasons, and also there happened to be a deli. The deli was=C2=A0almo=
st irrelevant to the stock, but not quite: If there wasn=E2=80=99t a deli =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0if the public company couldn=E2=80=99t put out filings with =
some description of some=C2=A0business and some financial statements =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then there couldn=E2=80=99t be a stock. The stock=E2=80=99s=C2=A0p=
rice=C2=A0had nothing to do with the deli, but the stock=E2=80=99s existenc=
e required=C2=A0the deli.
Similarly, DJT (the stock) is a $7 billion token, while Trump Media & Techn=
ology Group (the company) is fairly small; last year it lost $58 million on=
 $4 million of revenue.
  [1]
=C2=A0(=E2=80=9CAbout as lucrative as a top Substack newsletter,=E2=80=9D I=
 called it,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbut vastly more expensive to run.=E2=80=9D) But i=
f you take a small business=C2=A0with Trump=E2=80=99s name and ownership=C2=
=A0and wrap it in a stock, you can make=C2=A0a big meme stock.=C2=A0
We discussed this the other day, but it creates a lot of strange corporate =
issues. Consider the deli. What sort of salary would you expect to earn for=
 running the deli? One way to answer that question is to consider how much =
proprietors of other=C2=A0delis with $14,000 of annual revenues earn. (Not =
much!) Another way to answer the question is to consider how much chief exe=
cutive officers of other $2 billion public companies earn. (More!) Similarl=
y with DJT/TMTG: Should its executives get paid like the executives of a co=
mpany with $4 million of revenue, or one with $7 billion of market cap?
  [2]

Or here is a story from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Jef Feeley about a fight over t=
he division of the spoils:

Donald Trump has sued two co-founders of his newly public Trump Media & Tec=
hnology Group Corp., claiming they set the company up improperly and should=
n=E2=80=99t get any stock in it.
In the latest legal skirmish over who gets how much of the hot but flailing=
 meme stock, Trump alleges that Andy Litinsky and Wes Moss violated an agre=
ement about the setup and don=E2=80=99t deserve their 8.6% stake, currently=
 valued at $606 million.
The lawsuit, which was filed on March 24 in Florida state court and hasn=E2=
=80=99t previously been reported, comes after the pair brought their own su=
it against the former president in Delaware Chancery Court over their promi=
sed stake in the social media company.

Here is the complaint, which basically alleges that Litinsky and Moss =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cformer contestants on President Trump=E2=80=99s famous=
 television show,=C2=A0The Apprentice=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0did an incomp=
etent job of launching TMTG=E2=80=99s media business and finding a merger p=
artner. And, fine, I can believe that. (They=C2=A0did manage to find an ill=
egal=C2=A0merger partner.)
But I think that the broader point here is that Litinsky and Moss were hire=
d to set up TMTG=E2=80=99s rather small and speculative=C2=A0business, and =
it is absurd to reward them with 8.6% of DJT=E2=80=99s much larger=C2=A0mem=
e stock. My favorite part of the complaint is not actually in the complaint=
, but in the exhibit at the end, in which Trump=E2=80=99s lawyers reproduce=
 the Services Agreement between him and Litinsky and Moss. It just has a ve=
ry small-business feel, you know? Their role included =E2=80=9Censuring tha=
t TMG becomes an established entity registered under the laws of the state =
of Delaware =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and creating and implementing a strategic plan t=
o identify, exploit, and commercialize targeted media and technology opport=
unities in social media, internet infrastructure, podcast, digital streamin=
g, mobile apps, book publication, and television production.=E2=80=9D There=
 was not much vision; their job was to set up the company and look around f=
or something for it to do.
A schedule to the agreement lists =E2=80=9Cguidelines for reimbursable expe=
nses.=E2=80=9D Litinsky and Moss were entitled to reimbursement for =E2=80=
=9Ceconomy, coach or supersaver fares=E2=80=9D on flights and trains, thoug=
h =E2=80=9C21-day advance purchase is expected, when possible.=E2=80=9D Rea=
sonable hotel bills were reimbursable, "where under $150.00 per night is ty=
pically reasonable for most cities.=E2=80=9D Laundry and dry cleaning were =
=E2=80=9Cnot normally reimbursed for planned trips of less than 1 week.=E2=
=80=9D They had to submit receipts for =E2=80=9Cany individual expenditure =
of $10.00 or more.=E2=80=9D This is not Facebook Inc.=E2=80=99s charter, is=
 what I am saying here. This is =E2=80=9Cset up a small business for me, bu=
t don=E2=80=99t spend more than $150 a night on hotels.=E2=80=9D And now th=
ey might get $600 million!

