      Hunterbrook
   =20
 =20

I wrote yesterday that Hunterbrook, the hedge fund that is also a newspaper=
, is a sort of salary arbitrage. Hunterbrook Media is a news organization t=
hat employs reporters to write investigative stories, and then it gives tho=
se stories to Hunterbrook Capital, its affiliated hedge fund, to make trade=
s before the stories are published. If the stories are right and market-mov=
ing, then the hedge fund will make money, which it can use to pay for the n=
ews organization. I wrote: =E2=80=9CIt is expensive to hire hedge fund anal=
ysts to investigate companies all over the world. It is cheaper to hire jou=
rnalists!=E2=80=9D
But Hunterbrook also has another, much funnier expense arbitrage. It goes l=
ike this:
=09If you are a hedge fund conducting due diligence on a company, you will =
probably want to speak to experts. You might pay an expert-network firm to =
put you in touch with industry experts. You might engage consultants to eva=
luate the business. If you think the company might have legal issues, you w=
ill talk to specialist lawyers to help evaluate those issues. In each case,=
 you will call up the experts and say =E2=80=9Chi, I work at Hedge Fund X, =
we are evaluating Company Y, and we=E2=80=99d like to get your views.=E2=80=
=9D And those experts will probably say something like =E2=80=9Csure, that =
will be $2,000 per hour with a $10,000 minimum.=E2=80=9D And you=E2=80=99ll=
 say =E2=80=9Cyes perfect send an invoice to our billing department.=E2=80=
=9D You have a budget for this stuff.=09If you are a newspaper reporter inv=
estigating a company, you will probably want to speak to experts =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0industry experts, lawyers, etc. You will call up the experts and say =
=E2=80=9Chi, I am a reporter for the Z Daily News, I am writing a story abo=
ut Company Y, and I=E2=80=99d like to get your views.=E2=80=9D And those ex=
perts might say something like =E2=80=9Csure, I would love to get my name i=
n the paper, here is a pithy quote.=E2=80=9D Or they might say =E2=80=9CI d=
on=E2=80=99t want to be quoted, but on background =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D and th=
en tell you stuff. Or occasionally =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not that often =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0they might say =E2=80=9Csure I=E2=80=99ll talk to you, but I=E2=80=
=99ll need $2,000 per hour with a $10,000 minimum.=E2=80=9D In that case, y=
ou will say =E2=80=9Coh no, you don=E2=80=99t understand, I am a=C2=A0journ=
alist, it is unethical for me to pay sources.=E2=80=9D And then they=E2=80=
=99ll probably hang up, which is fine; you=E2=80=99ll call someone else who=
 wants to be quoted.

You see the arbitrage! Hunterbrook=E2=80=99s consulting budget is probably =
smaller than that of other hedge funds.
Yesterday Hunterbrook Media published its first big investigation, of Unite=
d Wholesale Mortgage, alleging that =E2=80=9CUWM=E2=80=99s conduct could co=
nstitute fraud and run afoul of laws passed after 2008 to protect borrowers=
.=E2=80=9D Hunterbrook Capital shorted UWM=E2=80=99s stock. If you want to =
figure out if a company=E2=80=99s conduct runs afoul of laws, one thing you=
 might do is call up a lawyer and say =E2=80=9Chey is this conduct legal?=
=E2=80=9D If you are a hedge fund and you do that, the lawyer will send you=
 a bill. If you are a media organization, maybe she won=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
And so in fact I heard yesterday from a lawyer who got that call (actually =
email) from Hunterbrook, and who replied to the effect of =E2=80=9Csure her=
e are my rates,=E2=80=9D and they replied to the effect of =E2=80=9Cno our =
ethics policy does not allow us to pay sources.=E2=80=9D From Hunterbrook=
=E2=80=99s website:=C2=A0

At Hunterbrook Media, we abide by the five traditional standards re: source=
 relationships, adapted from the New York Times:
1)=E2=80=83Financial Interactions: Don=CA=BCt pay sources, and don=CA=BCt l=
et them pay you (or pay for you).=C2=A0

The lawyer replied to the effect of =E2=80=9Cman you are not fooling me, wh=
en investment firms call me for analysis I charge them.=E2=80=9D They did n=
ot hire him. Also he forwarded me their exchange, commenting: =E2=80=9CNorm=
ally, conversations in search of legal counsel are subject to confidentiali=
ty obligations under legal ethics, but I don=E2=80=99t see how they can cla=
im they were seeking legal advice or that the inquiry was confidential. The=
y viewed me as a =E2=80=98source.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s true! They=
 weren=E2=80=99t looking to hire him as a lawyer, but to interview him as a=
 source, so he has no confidentiality obligations to them. If they had paid=
 him, he would.
In other Hunterbrook news, it=C2=A0disclosed yesterday=C2=A0that its =E2=80=
=9Cnonprofit affiliate has entered an agreement with [Boies Schiller Flexne=
r LLP]=C2=A0in exploration of a class action lawsuit against UWM seeking re=
stitution for homebuyers.=E2=80=9D The class action complaint was filed yes=
terday:

Over the past three years, UWM has issued nearly $39 billion in mortgages t=
hrough =E2=80=9Cindependent=E2=80=9D brokers who refer 99% of their busines=
s to UWM. And during last year alone, more than 8,000 so-called =E2=80=9Cin=
dependent=E2=80=9D brokers funneled 99% or more of their mortgages to UWM, =
worth at least $11.7 billion. In short, those brokers are not shopping arou=
nd to other lenders. They are not seeking the best prices for their princip=
als. They are instead captive to UWM. Through a series of intentional and i=
llegal practices, UWM has thus corrupted a large swath of =E2=80=9Cindepend=
ent=E2=80=9D brokers and turned them into the functional equivalent of the =
=E2=80=9Cloan officers=E2=80=9D that retail financial institutions use. The=
se corrupted brokers are in essence employees in the UWM enterprise. And wh=
ile doing that, both UWM and the corrupted brokers have concealed this fact=
 from consumers who have been led to believe their =E2=80=9Cindependent=E2=
=80=9D brokers are working for them and shopping around to multiple lenders=
.
The consequences to UWM=E2=80=99s borrowers have been devastating. UWM rare=
ly offered the best available pricing throughout the past four years and ro=
utinely charged fees that substantially exceeded their competitors=E2=80=99=
 offerings to the tune of billions of dollars. While UWM=E2=80=99s borrower=
s believed that their =E2=80=9Cindependent=E2=80=9D brokers were working fo=
r them, in reality, UWM induced thousands of these brokers to participate i=
n their funneling scheme and enterprise by successfully infiltrating and co=
rrupting their duties to the Plaintiffs and the class.

Presumably Boies Schiller plans to get paid.

